		<item>
		<title>Canada adopts law on assisted death</title>
		<link>http://www.newspages.co.za/canada-adopts-law-on-assisted-death/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 21 Jun 2016 07:49:39 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Khanyie]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Health]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Popular]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[World]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.newspages.co.za/?p=7263</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<img width="68" height="68" src="http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/hi-palliative-rtr2id7p-852-68x68.jpg" class="attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="hi-palliative-rtr2id7p-852" style="float: left; padding: 15px 15px 15px 0px;" />The Canadian government on Friday adopted a law allowing medically-assisted death for the terminally ill
<p>The new law brushed aside the critics, who wanted the legislation to cover people with degenerative diseases, Reuters reports.</p>
<p>According to Reuters, after weeks of political wrangling, the upper Senate Chamber voted in favour of a law which makes Canada one of the few nations where doctors can legally help sick people die.</p>
Some members of parliament were against the scope of the law saying it is too narrow and should not be restricted to those facing imminent death
<p>The Liberal government, though, narrowed the scope of the legislation to cover only those people whose death was reasonably foreseeable. Forward</p>
<p>Government officials said the new law is a first attempt to address a highly sensitive and controversial topic and could be broadened in years to come.</p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p>Ref: SA Breaking News</p>
<p> </p>
<p> </p>
]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img width="68" height="68" src="http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/hi-palliative-rtr2id7p-852-68x68.jpg" class="attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="hi-palliative-rtr2id7p-852" style="float: left; padding: 15px 15px 15px 0px;" /><h3>The Canadian government on Friday adopted a law allowing medically-assisted death for the terminally ill</h3>
<p>The new law brushed aside the critics, who wanted the legislation to cover people with degenerative diseases, <em>Reuters</em> reports.</p>
<p>According to Reuters, after weeks of political wrangling, the upper Senate Chamber voted in favour of a law which makes Canada one of the few nations where doctors can legally help sick people die.</p>
<h3>Some members of parliament were against the scope of the law saying it is too narrow and should not be restricted to those facing imminent death</h3>
<p>The Liberal government, though, narrowed the scope of the legislation to cover only those people whose death was reasonably foreseeable. Forward</p>
<p>Government officials said the new law is a first attempt to address a highly sensitive and controversial topic and could be broadened in years to come.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><em><strong>Ref: SA Breaking News</strong></em></p>
