		<item>
		<title>Half of adolescents have HIV in SA</title>
		<link>http://www.newspages.co.za/half-of-adolescents-have-hiv-in-sa/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 01 Dec 2015 07:11:55 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Tayla]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Africa]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Article]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Health]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Local News]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[South Africa]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Top Stories]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[World]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.newspages.co.za/?p=6745</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<img width="68" height="68" src="http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/aids-68x68.jpg" class="attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="aids" style="float: left; padding: 15px 15px 15px 0px;" /><p>South Africa is among six countries where over half the world&#8217;s adolescents living with HIV can be found. This was sighted by a senior UNAIDS official quoting a recent United Nations Children&#8217;s Fund study that found the number of adolescent deaths from AIDS-related illnesses has tripled since 2000.</p>
<p>To mark World Aids Day, The World Health Organisation and the Joint UN Programme on HIV/AIDS has emphasized expanding Anti-Retroviral Therapies to all people living with the virus is key to ending the epidemic by 2030.</p>
<p>Despite major strides in combatting the spread of HIV, AIDS is the leading cause of death among African teenagers and the second most common killer globally.</p>
<p>The UNAIDS office head, Simon Bland says, “ I talked about adolescent deaths tripping since 2000, that translates to 26 infections every hour. It&#8217;s the top cause of death for 15-19 year olds in Africa, the second largest cause of deaths for adolescents globally. I have seven out of 10 of those infections are girls, so girls way disproportionately affected other than boys. And half of these are in just six countries and so targeting those six countries is crucially important.”</p>
<p>Those six countries are South Africa, Nigeria, Kenya, Mozambique, Tanzania and India as the drive to close the gap between those infected and those on ARV treatment intensifies.</p>
<p>“If we look today at around 37 million people living with HIV and around 15 or 16 million people on treatment, there&#8217;s 21 million who need treatment today who don&#8217;t get it and around 19 million of those don&#8217;t know their status so there has to be a huge effort on testing, on getting the testing out.”</p>
<p>If we are to get on the fast-track to really beat this trajectory and end AIDS by 2030, we&#8217;ll need to invest even more than we&#8217;re investing today</p>
<p>“So innovations help with point of care diagnostics, cheaper and rapid diagnostics but it&#8217;s going to take a big push to get out there. We as part of our strategy have launched a target of 90-90-90 where by 2020 we want to get 90% of people infected with HIV tested so that they know their status, 90% of them having access to treatment and 90% of them having their virus suppressed,” Bland says.</p>
<p>Despite huge falls in infection rates, globally, around 2 million people became infected in 2014; 1.4 million in sub Saharan Africa with over one million deaths globally in the same year.</p>
<p>UNAIDS estimating that by 2020, they will require $ 31 billion annually to break the trajectory of the virus.</p>
<p>Bland says, “If we are to get on the fast-track to really beat this trajectory and end AIDS by 2030, we&#8217;ll need to invest even more than we&#8217;re investing today. Presently we calculate global investments of around 20 and 22 billion; we estimate that by 2020 we&#8217;ll need around 30-31 billion if we are to break the trajectory. 7.4 billion in low income countries, 10 billion in lower middle income countries and close to 14 million in upper middle income countries.”</p>
<p>The broad takeaway [...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img width="68" height="68" src="http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/aids-68x68.jpg" class="attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="aids" style="float: left; padding: 15px 15px 15px 0px;" /><p>South Africa is among six countries where over half the world&#8217;s adolescents living with HIV can be found. This was sighted by a senior UNAIDS official quoting a recent United Nations Children&#8217;s Fund study that found the number of adolescent deaths from AIDS-related illnesses has tripled since 2000.</p>
<p>To mark World Aids Day, The World Health Organisation and the Joint UN Programme on HIV/AIDS has emphasized expanding Anti-Retroviral Therapies to all people living with the virus is key to ending the epidemic by 2030.</p>
<p>Despite major strides in combatting the spread of HIV, AIDS is the leading cause of death among African teenagers and the second most common killer globally.</p>
<p>The UNAIDS office head, Simon Bland says, “ I talked about adolescent deaths tripping since 2000, that translates to 26 infections every hour. It&#8217;s the top cause of death for 15-19 year olds in Africa, the second largest cause of deaths for adolescents globally. I have seven out of 10 of those infections are girls, so girls way disproportionately affected other than boys. And half of these are in just six countries and so targeting those six countries is crucially important.”</p>
<p>Those six countries are South Africa, Nigeria, Kenya, Mozambique, Tanzania and India as the drive to close the gap between those infected and those on ARV treatment intensifies.</p>
<p>“If we look today at around 37 million people living with HIV and around 15 or 16 million people on treatment, there&#8217;s 21 million who need treatment today who don&#8217;t get it and around 19 million of those don&#8217;t know their status so there has to be a huge effort on testing, on getting the testing out.”</p>
<blockquote><p>If we are to get on the fast-track to really beat this trajectory and end AIDS by 2030, we&#8217;ll need to invest even more than we&#8217;re investing today</p></blockquote>
<p>“So innovations help with point of care diagnostics, cheaper and rapid diagnostics but it&#8217;s going to take a big push to get out there. We as part of our strategy have launched a target of 90-90-90 where by 2020 we want to get 90% of people infected with HIV tested so that they know their status, 90% of them having access to treatment and 90% of them having their virus suppressed,” Bland says.</p>
<p>Despite huge falls in infection rates, globally, around 2 million people became infected in 2014; 1.4 million in sub Saharan Africa with over one million deaths globally in the same year.</p>
<p>UNAIDS estimating that by 2020, they will require $ 31 billion annually to break the trajectory of the virus.</p>
<p>Bland says, “If we are to get on the fast-track to really beat this trajectory and end AIDS by 2030, we&#8217;ll need to invest even more than we&#8217;re investing today. Presently we calculate global investments of around 20 and 22 billion; we estimate that by 2020 we&#8217;ll need around 30-31 billion if we are to break the trajectory. 7.4 billion in low income countries, 10 billion in lower middle income countries and close to 14 million in upper middle income countries.”</p>
<p>The broad takeaway is that getting those carrying the virus onto ARV treatment is indeed lifesaving.</p>
<p>The rise in adolescent deaths over the last 15 years was often as a result of a lack of access to medication for those teenagers, many of whom were infected during infancy.</p>
<p>Despite broad availability of diagnostic testing globally, only half the people with HIV around the world know that they are carriers.</p>
<p>Thus closing the gap between knowing ones status and getting treatment remains among the biggest challenges in stopping the spread of HIV with the next 15 years.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
